					<p>A student seeking treatment for an eating disorder at Vanderbilt is generally directed to the PCC or the Zerfoss Student Health Center where they will be directed to the other center’s holistic treatment. Besides the team at the PCC, the Student Health Center houses two internists and a nutritionist whose availability has caused some concern. The nutritionist only sees patients for three hours a week at the clinic and works at the Adolescent and Young Adult Eating Disorders Program at Children’s Hospital at 100 Oaks for the rest of the time.</p>

					<div class="panel">
						<div class="panel-body bg-warning">
							<h5>Eating disorder treatment at the PCC</h5>
							<p>A further discussion with Catharine Fuchs, director of the PCC, provided more details on the process the PCC uses to diagnose and treat eating disorders.</p>
							<strong>The treatment process</strong>
							<ol>
								<li><strong>Assessment and stabilization: </strong>
										if a student presents with, for example, significant weight loss and fainting spells, the treatment needs to address the medical acuity in coordination with the Student Health Center
										if the student has a known history of anorexia but they are medically stable and maintain their weight within a safe range, they can move to the next phase immediately after assessment 
								</li>
								<li><strong>Harm reduction: </strong>
								the student in this phase is in a place where they are not harming themselves through unsafe eating patterns or self-injurious behaviors management of self-destructive thoughts is continued
								</li>
								<li>
									<strong>Evidence-based treatment: </strong>
										treatment is continued based on the individual presentation of the eating disorder
								</li>
